2669,IssuesEvent,2016-06-30 15:11:25+00:00,695611,etianen/django-reversion,5751476,felix-d,,,opened,Revision not showing in admin when creating a revision for a followed relationship with the decorator,[],[],0,"Hi! First of all thanks for that awesome library.

I have a model A and a model B with a foreign key relationship.

```python
@reversion.register(follow=['b'])
class A(models.Model):
    pass

@reversion.register()
class B(models.Model):
    a = models.ForeignKey(A)
```

When modifying an inlined instance of `B` in `A` ModelAdmin from the admin panel, I can see the revision in `A` instance admin page history tab.

When creating a revision with `@reversion.create_revision()` decorator and update an instance of `B`, the revision is not showing in the `A` instance admin page history tab.  

I tried to see what revisions are created from the shell when I use the decorator and it seems the revision for the `B` instance is created but not the revision for `A`, hence why it is not showing in the admin page.

If I do the modification from the admin page, the revision for `A` is created as it should.

Am I forgetting something?
",{},{}
2671,IssuesEvent,2016-04-21 18:41:43+00:00,695611,etianen/django-reversion,18601374,tarpack,,,opened,Unserializing foreign key / m2m relations,[],[],0,"I'm using django-reversion to store revisions of a bunch of different models, all of which have some sort of relations (whether foreign keys, many to many, or some kind of reverse relationship from a different model). On some of these models, I care about storing the related objects in the revision so I'm using `follow` when I register the model, on others I don't. It's all working great.

I don't use the django admin, so through the low level API I eventually end up with a `reversion.models.Version` object. I want to show the user what this version looked like. Using `field_dict` gets me most of the way there, except for the relations. If the model has a `colors` property that is a many to many relationship to a `Color` model, the dictionary entry is going to be something like:

    {...,
     'colors': [1, 23, 54],
     ...}

That isn't useful to the user.

So my question is, is there some generic way that I could recognize that the integers values in the dictionary are supposed to be the primary keys of an object, and what models those objects are, so that when I'm building the template I can get the actual objects and show them to the user?

In this case I know that the `colors` dictionary key is going to be a list of primary keys to `Color` objects, so when I'm looping through the dictionary I can look for that key and take special action when I get to it. But I can't think of some generic way to do this, that doesn't rely on some previous knowledge of the model.

Basically I want some kind of ""de-serializer"" function that I can pass a `reversion.models.Version` object to and get back something sort of object-like (whether it is actually an object or just another dictionary) that has followed the relationships to fetch the actual objects.

This seems like a common problem, but I'm not sure what the solution is!",{},{}
