4434,IssuesEvent,2015-01-20 13:39:35+00:00,14448779,astropy/astropy-helpers,314716,astrofrog,847984,astropy,opened,Consider renaming astropy-helpers in the long term,[],[],0,"Glue (http://glueviz.org) is an example of a non-astro-specific package where I think it would be nice to make use of astropy-helpers. We had previously discussed that in the long term we might consider renaming astropy-helpers to something more generic so that it can be used by non-astro packages (of course it *can* be used already, but having 'astro' in the name can make it sound like it is astro-specific). So this issue is just to start a conversation about whether we should consider renaming astropy-helpers to something else in future? (e.g. ``setup-helpers``?)",{},{}
4437,IssuesEvent,2018-05-10 20:12:41+00:00,104253938,astropy/pytest-remotedata,143715,keflavich,847984,astropy,opened,Allow `remote_data` to wrap `flaky`?,[],[],0,"In astroquery, we have persistent issues where the remote services are flaky, i.e., they do not always return responses.  We're now testing over a large enough grid that it is unlikely for all services to be online simultaneously ever.

As a workaround, it would be nice to use something like [flaky](https://github.com/box/flaky) or some other retry tool to re-run tests that fail for a configurable number of tries.  It would be convenient if this were made a configurable option of `remote_data`.  Might this be possible?  I haven't wrapped my head around the pytest infrastructure enough to understand whether it is.",{},{}
4441,IssuesEvent,2018-04-11 16:29:41+00:00,1953389,stripe/stripe-python,926355,louischatriot,856813,stripe,closed,Strange behavior of additional_owners field in Connect Custom accounts,[],[],5,"I found two behaviors quite strange when using the library, including something that may be a bug in the library.

**Issue 1**
When creating a Custom account, `additional_owners` cannot be passed as an array even though that's the format the API outputs, see code below:
```python
legal_entity_data = { 'first_name': 'something', 'additional_owners': [{ 'first_name': 'LLL' }] }
account_token = stripe.Token.create( account = { 'legal_entity': legal_entity_data, 'tos_shown_and_accepted': True })
# ^
# Raises an InvalidRequestError with message 'Invalid hash'
# But it works if we use { 0: { 'first_name' }: 'LLL' } ...
```

**Issue 2**
I can't remove any formerly created `additional_owners` by deleting the property on the Stripe account object as per https://stripe.com/docs/connect/account-tokens (though given there is no code example I may be interpreting the doc in the wrong way in which case would love to know what the right syntax is)

```python
legal_entity_data = { 'first_name': 'something', 'additional_owners': { 0: { 'first_name': 'LLL' }} }
account_token = stripe.Token.create( account = { 'legal_entity': legal_entity_data, 'tos_shown_and_accepted': True })
stripe_account = stripe.Account.create(type = 'custom', country = 'FR', account_token = account_token.id)

legal_entity_data = { 'first_name': 'another' }
account_token = stripe.Token.create( account = { 'legal_entity': legal_entity_data, 'tos_shown_and_accepted': True })
stripe_account = stripe.Account.retrieve(stripe_account['id'])   # Should be idempotent but just in case
stripe_account.account_token = account_token.id

del stripe_account.legal_entity.additional_owners
# ^
# This raises a KeyError even though the attribute does exit
# Same if I use stripe_account['legal_entity']['additional_owners']
# Btw being able to access properties both as attributes and dict keys smells a lot like magic
# and there seems to be some in `stripe_object.py`, from where the KeyError originates
#
# I also tried to set it to None but then the field is just not updated

stripe_account.save()
stripe_account = stripe.Account.retrieve(stripe_account['id'])   # Should be idempotent but just in case
assert(stripe_account['legal_entity']['first_name'] == 'another')   # Works, means the update did happen
assert(len(stripe_account['legal_entity']['additional_owners']) == 0)
```

This seems to be an issue with the lib given I was able to empty `additional_owners` with curl like so `curl https://api.stripe.com/v1/accounts/acct_1CFkpND1z7TNlJFl    -u MY_SECRET_KEY: -d legal_entity[additional_owners]=`


",{},{}
