4812,IssuesEvent,2016-07-03 09:53:58+00:00,24993138,google/brotli,7143443,GregSlazinski,1342004,google,opened,Functions to calculate approximate memory usage needed for compression and decompression,[],[],0,"Is it possible to provide such functions?
Such as :
int64 BrotliCompressionMemUsage(int quality, int lgwin, BrotliEncoderMode mode);
int64 BrotliDecompressionMemUsage(int quality, int lgwin, BrotliEncoderMode mode);

In my program, I use multi-threaded compression, by executing multiple compressors on multiple threads.
However I limit the number of simultaneous threads by the number of available memory .

For example if system has 4 GB of RAM.
And each call to compress function would require 1 GB of memory usage.
Based on that info I would know that I can create up to 4 threads.

However I was unable to find any information about memory usage for compressing and decompressing with Brotli.

Thank you",{},{}
4821,IssuesEvent,2016-02-04 20:20:24+00:00,24993138,google/brotli,8970895,jneb,1342004,google,opened,"Compression efficiency: found ""bad"" case",[],[],0,"This is not a complaint, but more of a ""teaser"".
In case someone in here tries to squeeze the last drop out of the compressor, I found (after trying about everything, where brotli consistently beats both gzip and bzip) an easy way to generate strings where both bzip2 and gzip do produce shorter strings than brotli.
I am convinced that there must be a way to get these shorter, so there must be some strange reason the compressor doesn't this. 

In English: make a list of random 10-bit patterns, written out in ASCII.
In Python3:
>>> ts='\n'.join('{:10b}\n'.format(random.getrandbits(10)) for i in range(1000))
>>> len(codecs.encode(bytes(ts,'ascii'),'zip'))
2373
>>> len(codecs.encode(bytes(ts,'ascii'),'bz2'))
2107
>>> len(brotli.compress((ts)))
2385
I hope this will inspire someone.",{},{}
