5886,IssuesEvent,2018-02-17 10:52:14+00:00,8763405,SoCo/SoCo,1611076,KennethNielsen,3826649,SoCo,closed,Make parsing errors in events less fatal,"[{'id': 562504490, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/SoCo/SoCo/labels/Bugfix', 'name': 'Bugfix', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': False}, {'id': 31825072, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/SoCo/SoCo/labels/Enhancement', 'name': 'Enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': False}, {'id': 806072659, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/SoCo/SoCo/labels/Has%20PR', 'name': 'Has PR', 'color': 'd9e00b', 'default': False}]",[],0,"Recently, many issues have arisen because Sonos doesn't adhere to the Didl spec, causing exceptions from from_didl_string - the next one's already at #520. The problem is exacerbated by the fact that for events, non-compliant metadata causes an exception at parsing time, which kills the subscription thread.
This behavior is unacceptable, especially if we are headed for a 1.0 release. I propose that we delay the exception until the user touches the faulty object, so he can handle it. We could modify the 'variables' dict to reraise the exception when the faulty variable is retrieved, or make a DidlFault object which reraises if anything is called on it. ",{},{}
5888,IssuesEvent,2016-11-03 19:54:14+00:00,8763405,SoCo/SoCo,1611076,KennethNielsen,3826649,SoCo,closed,SoCo on Windows - discovery does not work,[],[],7,"Hi,

maybe I am the only one using SoCo on Windows (7/10), but I cannot really believe that ;-). I use Linux as well as Windows - and on my machines (being Windows 7 or Windows 10, both 64bit versions) the `soco.discover()` call fails:

```
C:\Dev\Python35-2>python.exe
Python 3.5.2 (v3.5.2:4def2a2901a5, Jun 25 2016, 22:01:18) [MSC v.1900 32 bit (Intel)] on win32
Type ""help"", ""copyright"", ""credits"" or ""license"" for more information.
>>> import soco
>>> print(soco.discover())
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""C:\Dev\Python\Python35-32\lib\site-packages\soco\discovery.py"", line 123, in discover
    list(s.getsockname()[0] for s in _sockets))
  File ""C:\Dev\Python\Python35-32\lib\site-packages\soco\discovery.py"", line 123, in <genexpr>
    list(s.getsockname()[0] for s in _sockets))
OSError: [WinError 10022] An invalid argument was supplied
>>>
```

Funny enough, it is just a `_LOG` call that fails, so if you remove / comment out line 122+123 in `discovery.py`, everything works (although discovery is quite unstable with Windows - sometimes it works, sometimes not, but that is another story). I could not find a better way as removing the call yet.

BTW: I would love to participate in discussions in the SoCo Google Group, but someone needs to accept my request to join the group. Who can do that?

Thanks

  Jonas
",{},{}
5894,IssuesEvent,2017-11-21 22:55:44+00:00,49976939,learningequality/kolibri,191955,aronasorman,3926525,learningequality,closed,import/export progress bar can jump around with multiple channels,"[{'id': 492822760, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/learningequality/kolibri/labels/DEV:%20backend', 'name': 'DEV: backend', 'color': 'DFDFDF', 'default': False}, {'id': 667034570, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/learningequality/kolibri/labels/P0', 'name': 'P0', 'color': 'EB5A46', 'default': False}, {'id': 447172036, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/learningequality/kolibri/labels/TASK:%20bug', 'name': 'TASK: bug', 'color': '72486f', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'jonboiser', 'id': 10248067, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/10248067?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/jonboiser', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/jonboiser/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, {'login': 'lyw07', 'id': 19424916, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars2.githubusercontent.com/u/19424916?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/lyw07', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lyw07/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",21,"
As indicated in https://github.com/learningequality/kolibri/issues/1882#issuecomment-319135695 the progress bar jumps around when multiple channels are being imported or exported. 

From a user's perspective, one would expect progress to reflect the cumulative progress of all channels in the pipeline.

",{},{}
