It's exactly like https://github.com/deis/deis/blob/e2c06895ec5202a751cfb2b61f8b64039de98a2e/contrib/coreos/user-data.example with the mandatory adjustments made.

I have three nodes, cloud-1, cloud-2 and cloud-3, and they have the IPs 10.250.0.11, 10.250.0.12, 10.250.0.13, respectively.

I installed the nodes with this command:

    coreos-install -C stable -c user-data.1.txt -d /dev/sda -V 647.2.0

(user-data.1.txt is the user-data file configured for the 10.250.0.11 host.)

I am able to log into any of those node after they boot and they do find each other:

    core@cloud-1 ~ $ fleetctl list-machines
    MACHINE		IP		METADATA
    07efeeec...	10.250.0.13	-
    499e43f8...	10.250.0.11	-
    73b7dcd6...	10.250.0.12	-

Sure enough, from my control machine I executed:

    $ deisctl --version
    1.9.0
    $ deisctl install platform
    ● ▴ ■
    ■ ● ▴ Installing Deis...
    ▴ ■ ●
    Storage subsystem...
    [shortened]
