6421,IssuesEvent,2017-05-30 07:48:35+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,3583940,martinfiers,6392739,conda,closed,Installing a tar bundle,"[{'id': 360414999, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/source:community', 'name': 'source:community', 'color': 'c2e0c6', 'default': False}, {'id': 16544532, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/conda/conda/labels/type:feature', 'name': 'type:feature', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}]",[],8,"Hello,

According to: 

https://docs.continuum.io/anaconda/faq#how-do-i-install-packages-on-a-non-networked-machine

You can install a bundle of packages by first creating a tar, and then simply using ``conda install``. The bundle would just install them without doing any checking - which is indeed the desired behavior if you're assuming you created a consistent bundle.

I found out that this works nicely on conda 4.2.12, but not anymore on 4.3.17 (I didn't test versions in between).

Is there a reason this behavior has changed (and, certainly, the doc is out of sync with the latest behavior). 

What would be the preferred way to make a 'bundle' of packages? My use case is that we have a proper environment already set up, and I want to deploy additional packages in that environment (which have been tested to work and do not create dependency problems).

Thanks for looking into this and advising!",{},{}
6431,IssuesEvent,2017-05-10 01:48:08+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,1418419,kalefranz,6392739,conda,closed,change default directory in launcher,[],[],1,"I would like to change the default directory for launcher.  According to the docs,

---

Each time Launcher is run it will check for a file called .anaconda-launcher.rc in the user’s home directory (~).

If the file doesn’t exist Launcher will create it with the default settings. 

---

however, the default file is not created by Launcher.

I'm using Windows 7 and Miniconda2
",{},{}
