6510,IssuesEvent,2018-04-24 13:53:14+00:00,16557526,pysam-developers/pysam,1761258,kmhernan,6598771,pysam-developers,opened,fetch using region string doesn't work for contigs with '-' in the name,[],[],0,"I'm pretty sure the culprit is the splitting section here https://github.com/pysam-developers/pysam/blob/master/pysam/libchtslib.pyx#L656-L657

For example:

```
>>> region = 'HCV-1:9400-9500'
>>> re.split('[:-]', region)
['HCV', '1', '9400', '9500']
>>> parts = re.split('[:-]', region)
>>> contig = parts[0]
>>> contig
'HCV'
```

And in pysam fetch:

```
>>> vfil.fetch(region='HCV-1:9400-9500')
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File ""pysam/libcbcf.pyx"", line 4342, in pysam.libcbcf.VariantFile.fetch
  File ""pysam/libchtslib.pyx"", line 675, in pysam.libchtslib.HTSFile.parse_region
ValueError: invalid contig `HCV`
```

But I can do it outside of the region string:

```
>>> list(vfil.fetch('HCV-1', 9400, 9500))
[<pysam.libcbcf.VariantRecord object at 0x7fee797356d8>]
```",{},{}
6513,IssuesEvent,2017-08-07 17:27:40+00:00,6347889,django-admin-bootstrapped/django-admin-bootstrapped,663459,rfadams,6607971,django-admin-bootstrapped,opened,"Not compatible with Django 1.11, getting ""TypeError: context must be a dict rather than RequestContext.""",[],[],0,"First, thanks for all the hard work that went into this library. I've used it on several projects and really enjoy it. 

Today, I'm using it on a project that is Django 1.11.4. I found that the section for [including templates to the change form](https://github.com/django-admin-bootstrapped/django-admin-bootstrapped#add-custom-html-to-the-change-form-of-any-model-with-a-template) was not working. After much confusion, I found that in Django 1.11 the `render_to_string` method (used [here](https://github.com/django-admin-bootstrapped/django-admin-bootstrapped/blob/master/django_admin_bootstrapped/templatetags/bootstrapped_goodies_tags.py#L18)) now requires a `dict` instead of `Context()` / `RequestContext()`. 

I added some logging and eventually saw the error:
```TypeError: context must be a dict rather than RequestContext.```

I found these two key sources discussing the matter:

- https://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/27722
- https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.11/releases/1.11/#django-template-backends-django-template-render-prohibits-non-dict-context

To resolve the issue, I forked and created a PR. Only after all this effort did I see that this library was capped at Django 1.9 and I haven't tested its complete compatibility with Django 1.10 or 1.11 but it seems to be working well for me now. I wanted to post up this issue in case others were looking around as well. 

",{},{}
