7540,IssuesEvent,2015-04-25 19:08:52+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,2379650,sloria,10334301,marshmallow-code,closed,Default field values,[],[],7,"Most typed fields (`String`, `Integer`, `Decimal`) have default values of the corresponding type: `String` defaults to `''`, `Integer` to `0`, etc. This has the desirable effect of making serialized types predictable, but also introduces some potentially counter-intuitive behavior: attributes set to `None` are serialized as `''`, `0`, etc:

```python
class Model(Base):
    id = sa.Column(sa.Integer, primary_key=True)
    count = sa.Column(sa.Integer, nullable=True)

class Schema(ma.Schema):
    count = ma.fields.Integer()

row = Model(id=1)
Schema().dump(row).data    # {""id"": 1, ""count"": 0}
```

In this example, using SQLAlchemy, `count` is a nullable column: `None` values are allowed, and probably mean something different from `0`. I wasn't expecting `None` to be serialized to `0`--I actually only noticed because I was refactoring some code to use Marshmallow, and I broke some tests.

In this case, I can get the behavior I want by explicitly setting a `default` value for the schema field: `count = ma.fields.Integer(default=None)`. But I'm wondering whether that should be the default behavior of Marshmallow. It makes fewer assumptions about developers' intentions, and I think it would be less [surprising](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principle_of_least_astonishment). It would also make behavior a little more consistent across field subclasses: most subclasses use a non-`None` default value, but `DateTime` actually defaults to `None`.

Proposal: All fields (other than `List`, or with `many` set to `True`) should default to `None` unless a different default is provided by the developer.",{},{}
7542,IssuesEvent,2015-04-12 17:33:58+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,509198,m1kola,10334301,marshmallow-code,opened,UnmarshallingError with None value in DateTime,[],[],0,"When your schema contains `DateTime` field (even if `required=False`) and you trying to update this field (with `PATCH` method, for example) `UnmarshalResult` exception will be raised.

I think same result will be with all date\time fileds: `DateTime`, `LocalDateTime`, `Time`, `Date`, 

**Example:**
```Python
from marshmallow import fields, Schema


class TestSchema(Schema):
    string_field = fields.String()
    datetime_field = fields.DateTime()


schema = TestSchema()
schema.load({'datetime_field': None})
```
Result of this code will be `UnmarshalResult`:
```
UnmarshalResult(data={'datetime_field': None}, errors={'datetime_field': [u'Could not deserialize None to a datetime object.']})
```

**Workaround:**
You can extend `DateTime` field like this:
```Python
from marshmallow import fields


class DateTime(fields.DateTime):
    """"""Same as the DateTime from marshmallow.fields,
    but allows datetime to be None
    """"""

    def _deserialize(self, value):
        if not self.required and value is None:
            return value

        return super(DateTime, self)._deserialize(value)
```

**Code:**
Problem in `_deserialize` method of `DateTime`, `Time` and `Date` classes. [Example](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/blob/1.2.4/marshmallow/fields.py#L955) from `DateTime`:
```Python
        msg = 'Could not deserialize {0!r} to a datetime object.'.format(value)
        err = UnmarshallingError(getattr(self, 'error', None) or msg)
        if not value:  # Falsy values, e.g. '', None, [] are not valid
            raise err
```
Other fields have similar checks.

**Version:** 1.2.4",{},{}
