8385,IssuesEvent,2018-08-09 16:05:50+00:00,1404690,PmagPy/PmagPy,1836578,moonshoes87,16460206,PmagPy,opened,make_magic_plots improvements for the server,[],[],0,"We will want to include more information for isServer, and improve formatting.

- contribution id should be included in plots
- fix formatting issues
- title should be displayed in plot not filename

Ultimately, we should have an images table (image name can be simple, just 1.png, 2.png)

Error logging:

basic case for each potential plot:
fails because of bug
fails because of missing data
succeeds

It would be great to know which it is.

If we can't have that, we should do some simple checks, i.e.:

Were any plots produced?  If there are sites and locations, we should expect some plots.

Possibly ways to handle the error logging:
- if an image should be created but isn't , create that as a text file with the error message
if not, a log with one line per file it failed to make
log can also plotting times, can be verbose

We can have a verbose option with stack traces etc. for us, and a more low-key option for users.

Check contribution 16350 as an example.
",{},{}
8389,IssuesEvent,2018-07-28 12:54:52+00:00,74367336,datosgobar/pydatajson,1264073,poligarcia,16464674,datosgobar,closed,Robustecer la función `distribution_has_time_index` para que no se rompa,"[{'id': 592494835, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw1OTI0OTQ4MzU=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/datosgobar/pydatajson/labels/2%20sp', 'name': '2 sp', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}, {'id': 485928289, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0ODU5MjgyODk=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/datosgobar/pydatajson/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ee0701', 'default': True}, {'id': 491029324, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw0OTEwMjkzMjQ=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/datosgobar/pydatajson/labels/in%20progress', 'name': 'in progress', 'color': 'ededed', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'lrromero', 'id': 35603585, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjM1NjAzNTg1', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars0.githubusercontent.com/u/35603585?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/lrromero', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/lrromero/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"**Contexto**

Actualmente si el campo `field` de una distribución no tiene la estructura esperada, la función presume que puede realizar acciones contra ella para validar si tiene o no un índice de tiempo que pueden fallar (como presumir que hay un `dict` contra el que hacer un `get`).

**Propuesta**

Re-factorizar la función con un `try` `except` (o con cualquier otra estrategia) para que si falla por cualquier motivo interprete que la distribución *no tiene un índice de tiempo*.

La justificación detrás es que la función *sólo devuelve True cuando consigue encontrar una distribución que cumple con la especificación de series de tiempo para tener un índice de tiempo, si esto no es así - por el motivo que sea - se considera que la distribución _no tiene un índice de tiempo_*, pero no rompe.",{},{}
8401,IssuesEvent,2016-10-14 20:16:42+00:00,55101236,googleapis/artman,8572251,landrito,16785467,googleapis,closed,Stop using packman for Ruby gRPC client generation,[],"[{'login': 'landrito', 'id': 8572251, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/8572251?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/landrito', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/landrito/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",8,"Derived from #69:

Currently Ruby gRPC client pipeline use packman to generate gRPC files. However, that does not fit with the design of gcloud-ruby, where a package contains all of hand-written layers, Gapic-generated files, and gRPC-generated files.
That is Cloud APIs only, but there are no strong reasons to split packages for Gapic files and gRPC files in Ruby.

Because of that, we should stop using packman for Ruby's client pipeline. Instread, similar to Java, we should use protoc_tasks we already have.

Also, from https://github.com/googleapis/artman/issues/69#issuecomment-242172115,

> Currently we get protoc from linuxbrew here: https://github.com/grpc/homebrew-grpc
> That site indicates that the linuxbrew method is deprecated for all languages except C/C++. 

Therefore, Ruby will use grpc-tools rubygem (https://rubygems.org/gems/grpc-tools).

Cc: @bjwatson @geigerj ",{},{}
