9060,IssuesEvent,2018-06-09 01:20:59+00:00,48904888,Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot,3731082,tekulvw,23690422,Cog-Creators,closed,[V3] Meaningful responses to bad command arguments,"[{'id': 924035711, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw5MjQwMzU3MTE=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot/labels/PR%20Pending', 'name': 'PR Pending', 'color': 'e8874e', 'default': False}, {'id': 593836458, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw1OTM4MzY0NTg=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot/labels/V3', 'name': 'V3', 'color': '006b75', 'default': False}]",[],6,"Right now, when a ""Bad Argument"" is passed into a command (i.e. when a `commands.Converter` fails), the bot simply responds with the help message. This doesn't really tell the user why the command failed, and I've seen many users be stumped by this.

I have two ideas for solutions:
1. Respond saying exactly what conversion failed, e.g. if a `commands.MemberConverter` fails, it responds with _Member ""[user]"" not found_
2. Make the help message contain better documentation for command arguments.

Disadvantages of each solution:
1. Relies on a meaningful message being passed into `commands.BadArgument` when a conversion fails, which brings up potential issues with custom converters (there are no guidelines on how `commands.BadArgument` should be used).
2. A more meaningful help message is still fairly ambiguous. The point of error messages is for the user to know exactly what went wrong, not just throwing a bunch of help docs in their face.",{},{}
